<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="282" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,647,826,876]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">
ETYMOLOGY. — Named for the lobate form of the uropodal rami, and an anagram of “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Packard" authorityYear="1886" box="[429,535,852,876]" class="Malacostraca" family="Belotelsonidae" genus="Belotelson" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Belotelsonidea" pageId="5" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Belotelson</taxonomicName>
”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="282" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[112,647,899,1055]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">DIAGNOSIS. — Moderate to small belotelsonid; rostrum length approximately equal to carapace length, gently curving upward along its length. Thoracopodal endopods long, thin, slit-like, with propodus extremely long. Uropodal rami distinctly lobate, apparently thin and not well sclerotized.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="282" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[112,647,1103,1192]" box="[113,213,1103,1129]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[112,647,1103,1192]" pageId="5" pageNumber="282">The distinctive form of the rostrum and the unique tail fan warrant a separate genus for this species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
